Interface IUndirectedGraph<NodeType>

  • Type Parameters:
    NodeType - The type of the nodes.
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AUndirectedGraph

    public interface IUndirectedGraph<NodeType>
    Represents a graph whose nodes are of type NodeType.

      • addNode

        void addNode(NodeType node)
        Adds a node to this graph, if it is not already present. No edges will be added; the node will initially be its own connected component, until the user adds edges using addEdge(...). If the node is already present in the graph (true if there exists a node x in the graph for which node.equals(x).
        Parameters:
        node - The node to add.

      • getNodes

        java.util.Set<NodeType> getNodes()
        Return a set of all nodes in the graph. Implementors should take care to ensure that the graph is not corrupted by an alteration of the returned set. The returned set should either not be used to back the graph in any way, be modified only to support read-only behavior, or be modified to update the graph when write operations occur.
        Returns:
        A set of all nodes in the graph.

      • getNeighbors

        java.util.Set<NodeType> getNeighbors(NodeType node)
        Return a set of all nodes that are connected via a single edge to node. Implementors should take care to ensure that the graph is not corrupted by an alteration of the returned set. The returned set should either not be used to back the graph in any way, be modified only to support read-only behavior, or be modified to update the graph when write operations occur.
        Parameters:
        node - The node whose neighbors to provide.
        Returns:
        The neighbors of the specified node.

      • aStar

        java.util.List<NodeType> aStar(NodeType start,
                             NodeType end,
                             IDistanceEstimator<NodeType> distanceEstimator)
        Perform A* on the graph to find the optimal path from the start node to the end node. If a path is found, it will be returned via the list. If no path is found, an empty list will be returned.
        Parameters:
        start - The node at which the path should start.
        end - The node to be reached via the path.
        distanceEstimator - An instance which can be used to estimate distances between nodes in the graph.
        Returns:
        A list representing the path from the start node to the end node, or an empty list if no path exists. If a path is found, the first element of the list should be the start node, and the last element should be the end node. Each node traversed on the way from the start node to the end node should appear exactly once in the list. Therefore, if a path from node a were calculated to node d, via the edges (a, b), (b, c), and (c, d), the returned list should consist of [a, b, c, d].
